Freehold Township, nestled in the western expanse of [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey) within the [U.S. state](/U.S._state) of [New Jersey](/New_Jersey), presents itself as a rather predictable tableau of modern American life. It’s a place where major highways intersect, creating a commercial nexus for [Central New Jersey](/Central_Jersey), boasting the venerable [Freehold Raceway](/Freehold_Raceway) and the omnipresent [Freehold Raceway Mall](/Freehold_Raceway_Mall). Beyond its commercial aspirations, the township functions primarily as a [suburban](/Suburb) [bedroom community](/Commuter_town) for the relentless churn of [New York City](/New_York_City), firmly ensconced within the [Raritan Valley Region](/Raritan_River) of the far larger [New York Area](/New_York_metropolitan_area). [18][19][20] For those who choose to endure the daily pilgrimage, [Manhattan](/Manhattan) lies approximately 38 miles (61 km) to the east, while the slightly less daunting journey to [Staten Island](/Staten_Island) is about 20 miles (32 km) away. [21][22]

According to the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census), the township's population stood at 35,369. [8][9] This marked a slight, perhaps even insignificant, decrease of 815 residents, or a −2.3% shift, from the 36,184 individuals counted during the [2010 census](/2010_United_States_census). [23][24] That earlier figure, in turn, represented a more robust increase of 4,647 people (+14.7%) from the 31,537 recorded in the [2000 census](/2000_United_States_census). [25] One might observe that the ebb and flow of human habitation continues, largely unimpeded by grand pronouncements or even minor statistical dips.

Freehold Township, in its current administrative form, first materialized on October 31, 1693, a date that probably meant more to the land speculators than to the land itself. It was formally [incorporated](/Municipal_corporation) as a township by an act of the [New Jersey Legislature](/New_Jersey_Legislature) on February 21, 1798. The bureaucratic ballet of territorial division began early: portions of Freehold Township were carved out to establish [Upper Freehold Township](/Upper_Freehold_Township,_New_Jersey) around 1731. This historical detail explains why some wills and official records post-split rather confusingly referred to "Lower Freehold Township," despite the official designation consistently remaining "Freehold Township." [26][27] Additional geographical excisions followed, creating [Millstone Township](/Millstone_Township,_New_Jersey) on February 28, 1844; [Jackson Township](/Jackson_Township,_New_Jersey) on March 6, 1844; [Atlantic Township](/Colts_Neck_Township,_New_Jersey) (now known as Colts Neck Township) on February 18, 1847; [Marlboro Township](/Marlboro_Township,_New_Jersey) on February 17, 1848; and [Manalapan Township](/Manalapan_Township,_New_Jersey) on March 9, 1848. The borough that now lies at its heart, [Freehold Borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey), was initially established as a [town](/Town_(New_Jersey)) *within* the township on March 25, 1869, before achieving formal separation and reconstitution as a distinct borough on April 15, 1919, a process which even then involved annexing further portions of the surrounding township. [28]

It is also worth noting, for those who appreciate historical footnotes, that the pivotal [Battle of Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth) was fought in June 1778 within the very lands that comprise parts of both Freehold Township and [Manalapan](/Manalapan_Township,_New_Jersey) today, an area now meticulously preserved as [Monmouth Battlefield State Park](/Monmouth_Battlefield_State_Park). [29]

### History

#### Early

Before the inevitable arrival of Europeans, the [Lenni Lenape](/Lenape) Native Americans were the earliest documented inhabitants of the area now known as Freehold. Their existence, unlike the frantic pace of modern life, was defined by a more harmonious integration with the natural world. They operated as a [hunter-gatherer](/Hunter-gatherer) society, largely sedentary, adapting their campsites with the changing seasons. Their diet was diverse, relying on proficient hunting of small game and birds, alongside their notable skill as fishermen, harvesting considerable quantities of clams from the various bays and inlets along the [Jersey Shore](/Jersey_Shore). To supplement their wild bounty, they also engaged in rudimentary agriculture. During this era, a crucial intersection of two significant Lenape trails existed within the Freehold area, suggesting its historical importance as a point of convergence long before the advent of paved roads and strip malls. [30][31]

The first European to cast eyes upon this land, according to historical accounts, was [John Cabot](/John_Cabot) in 1498, a fleeting glance that foreshadowed a more permanent, and disruptive, presence. By the latter half of the 17th century, the English began their systematic acquisition and colonization of the region. In 1664, the [Duke of York](/Duke_of_York) (who would later ascend to the throne as [James II & VII](/James_II_of_England)) issued [a patent](/Monmouth_Tract) to [Sir George Carteret](/Sir_George_Carteret), granting him authority to develop this newly claimed territory. The first substantial wave of European settlers arrived in 1685, comprising Scottish [Presbyterians](/Presbyterians) from [Scotland](/Scotland), alongside English [Baptists](/Baptists) and [Quakers](/Quakers) hailing from [New England](/New_England), all seeking refuge from the religious persecution that had driven them from their homelands. [30][32]

It was in 1693 that Freehold, alongside its counterparts [Middletown](/Middletown_Township,_New_Jersey) and [Shrewsbury](/Shrewsbury_Township,_New_Jersey), was formally established by legislative act as one of the three foundational townships within [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey). [33] The name itself, "Freehold," is derived from the English legal term [freehold](/Freehold_(law)), which denotes a form of [fee simple](/Fee_simple) property ownership. A rather practical, if uninspired, choice, highlighting the primary motivation of its new inhabitants: land and the right to possess it. [34]

#### Colonial

The year 1714 marked a particularly self-serving moment in Freehold's nascent history. As the colonial government deliberated on the optimal location for the county seat and its indispensable courthouse, a prominent Freeholder named John Reid, who also happened to be the first [Surveyor General](/Surveyor_General) of [East Jersey](/East_Jersey), [35] conveniently advocated for Freehold. His offer to sell the necessary property to the [Board of Chosen Freeholders](/Board_of_County_Commissioners_(New_Jersey)) at a heavily discounted price proved to be a decisive factor, tipping the scales in Freehold's favor over rival claims from Middletown or Shrewsbury. As a testament to Reid's foresight, or perhaps his lingering distrust, he embedded a [restrictive covenant](/Restrictive_covenant) within the deed: should the property ever cease its function as a courthouse, ownership would revert directly to the Reid family. It is a detail that speaks volumes about the enduring human desire for legacy and control. Intriguingly, direct descendants of John Reid are said to still reside within Freehold Township, a quiet echo of its founding. [36]

The [Monmouth Courthouse](/Monmouth_County_Courthouse), the linchpin of this arrangement, officially opened its doors in 1715. Around this central pillar of justice and administration, a small village, initially known as Monmouth Courthouse, began to coalesce with a predictable efficiency. Over time, other governmental structures emerged in its vicinity, including a sheriff's office, a prison (a necessity, it seems, in any burgeoning community), and a post office. The burgeoning settlement also attracted a familiar array of commercial enterprises and residences: a blacksmith, a general store, a bank, a hotel, and, of course, a saloon – catering to both the essential and the less essential needs of the populace. [38]

Beyond the nascent urbanity of Monmouth Courthouse, the surrounding lands flourished with successful farms. Freehold's agricultural output gained particular renown for its potatoes, beans, and rye, which found ready markets in the nearby, larger cities. The region also cultivated a reputation for its excellent horse farms, a testament to its fertile soil and diligent cultivators. [31] This burgeoning dichotomy between the concentrated settlement around the courthouse and the expansive, productive farmland laid the groundwork for the eventual, almost inevitable, division of Freehold into two distinct municipalities in the early 20th century. A classic tale of differing priorities and incompatible aspirations.

By 1745, the demographic tapestry of Freehold was still predominantly woven with threads of Scottish immigration. [39] Even today, many of the significant streets in modern Freehold bear the surnames of these early colonial families, names such as Barkalow, Applegate, Rhea, Throckmorton, and Schanck, serving as quiet, enduring markers of their initial settlement. [39]

#### Revolutionary War

[[File:Craig House, Freehold Township.jpg|thumb|This 18th Century home, also known as the [Craig House](/Craig_House_(New_Jersey)), was [quartered](/Quartering_Acts) by British troops during the Battle of Monmouth [40]]]

*   See also: [Battle of Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth)

The [American Revolution](/American_Revolution), that tumultuous period of ideological and martial upheaval, left an indelible mark on Freehold. In 1765, following the much-resented passage of the [Stamp Act](/Stamp_Act), pockets of dissent began to coalesce. Citizens in Middletown and [Upper Freehold](/Upper_Freehold_Township,_New_Jersey) established local chapters of the [Sons of Liberty](/Sons_of_Liberty), signaling their growing dissatisfaction with British rule. [41] By late 1775, Captain Elias Longstreet managed to recruit the county's first company of colonists to join the fledgling Continental Army, embarking on an ill-fated invasion of Canada, a venture that perhaps underscored the nascent army's ambition more than its strategic prowess. [42] Freehold, even then, was recognized as a hotbed of patriot activity, a place where revolutionary fervor simmered. The [Declaration of Independence](/U.S._Declaration_of_Independence) was not merely a document; it was a public spectacle, read aloud from the steps of the [Monmouth Courthouse](/Monmouth_County_Courthouse) just days after its signing in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). [39]

Following the British's rather decisive success at the [Battle of Long Island](/Battle_of_Long_Island), Freehold and the entirety of [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey) regrettably fell under the control of [Loyalists](/Loyalist_(American_Revolution)). [43] The British government, ever keen on maintaining a veneer of normalcy, continued to operate the Monmouth Courthouse, transforming it into a venue for prosecuting perceived traitors. Consequently, several individuals involved in revolutionary activities found themselves arrested and tried for treason within its very walls. [43] The tide, however, began to turn with the Continental Army's unexpected success at the [Battle of Trenton](/Battle_of_Trenton), a victory that significantly eroded loyalist control over Freehold. [44]

June 1778 saw the British Army embark on a major strategic evacuation from [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). Their objective was to safeguard a lengthy, slow-moving column laden with Loyalist families, military equipment, and other supplies they had judiciously seized from Philadelphia, as they painstakingly made their way towards ships awaiting them in [New York Harbor](/New_York_Harbor). On June 28, 1778, the Continental Army, under the watchful eye of [George Washington](/George_Washington), intercepted this procession in Freehold. [45] The ensuing [Battle of Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth) became one of the largest engagements of the entire Revolutionary War, drawing a combined force of over 25,000 soldiers from Continental, British, and [Hessian](/Hessian_(soldiers)) ranks. The initial phase of the battle was, to put it mildly, a chaotic affair, with the outcome hanging precariously in the balance until Washington's timely arrival. His subordinate, [Charles Lee](/Charles_Lee_(general)), had been in the process of an ignominious retreat from the battlefield, a decision that would later lead to his court-martial. Washington, with characteristic resolve, rallied the Continental forces, engaging the British in a fierce confrontation that ultimately saw them hold their ground. While the British achieved their primary objective – the evacuation of Philadelphia – both sides, with a predictable lack of humility, ultimately claimed victory in the battle. [45]

[[File:Molly Pitcher at Battle of Monmouth.jpg|thumb|Molly Pitcher fighting at the Battle of Monmouth in Freehold, New Jersey]]

The Battle of Monmouth was a veritable who's who of Revolutionary War figures. British forces were commanded by the formidable [Sir Henry Clinton](/Henry_Clinton_(American_War_of_Independence)) and [Charles Cornwallis](/Charles_Cornwallis). On the American side, [George Washington](/George_Washington) and the aforementioned [Charles Lee](/Charles_Lee_(general)) led the charge. Beyond these central figures, other notable personalities included [Nathanael Greene](/Nathanael_Greene), [Alexander Hamilton](/Alexander_Hamilton), the rather dramatically named ["Mad" Anthony Wayne](/Anthony_Wayne), the aristocratic [Marquis de Lafayette](/Marquis_de_Lafayette), and the disciplined [Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben](/Friedrich_Wilhelm_von_Steuben), all contributing to the Continental Army's efforts. [46] Another enduring figure from the battle, one who has transcended historical record to enter the realm of legend, was [Molly Pitcher](/Molly_Pitcher), who famously stepped in to man a cannon after her husband was wounded, a testament to the unexpected heroism that often emerges from the crucible of war. [46]

In the wake of the Battle of Monmouth, Loyalist control over Freehold irrevocably crumbled. The township found itself without a functioning municipal government, and the courthouse remained shuttered until the war's conclusion. Minor skirmishes between Loyalists and Continentals continued to erupt within the town, with the violence reaching its peak around 1780. [47] A particularly infamous figure of this period was [Colonel Tye](/Colonel_Tye), an escaped slave formerly known as Titus, who became the leader of a prominent Loyalist guerrilla force. Tye and his men conducted several raids in and around Freehold, a testament to the complex and often brutal loyalties of the war. In one such notorious incident, [Joshua Huddy](/Joshua_Huddy) was captured and summarily hanged by British [Loyalists](/Loyalist_(American_Revolution)) under the direction of Richard Lippincott and Colonel Tye himself. Colonel Tye later succumbed to injuries sustained during that very raid. [48] Patriots, in a defiant act, later cut down Huddy's body from the gallows and interred it in Freehold, at the venerable [Old Tennent Church](/Old_Tennent_Church). [49] The war's end did not bring immediate peace of mind; the community was deeply fragmented, leading nearly 120 Loyalist families to flee Freehold, fearing retribution from their former neighbors. Most of these displaced families sought new beginnings in Canada, a quiet exodus marking the profound social upheaval of the era. [50]

#### 19th century

The early 1800s saw Freehold experience a steady, if unremarkable, expansion. The village that had grown around the courthouse now shared the name Freehold with the surrounding agricultural lands. [51] By 1852, with the advent of long-distance railroad systems, a significant development arrived: a railroad station, complete with regular train stops, was constructed, running nearly parallel to Throckmorton Street in Freehold. This technological leap brought with it the trappings of modernity. Freehold soon boasted public sewers in its village core and even in some of the more affluent outlying farmland. By 1883, the township had established an electrical grid and a telephone switchboard, conveniences that were still considered cutting-edge innovations at the time. [51] These public infrastructure advancements acted as a catalyst for rapid economic growth, transforming the village of Freehold into an important commercial and industrial hub for [central New Jersey](/Central_Jersey). The surrounding farms also reaped significant benefits, finding it considerably easier to transport and sell their produce in the burgeoning markets of [New York](/New_York_City) and [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). [52] The village and its agricultural periphery, despite their mutual prosperity, found their public policy priorities increasingly diverging, setting the stage for future disagreements within the municipal government, which became progressively divided between the interests of the villagers and the farmers.

In 1824, the American Hotel opened its doors on Main Street in Freehold. It stands to this day, a silent observer of centuries of change, and remains one of the oldest surviving buildings in the area. The year 1853 marked the inauguration of the [Freehold Raceway](/Freehold_Raceway), a landmark institution. [53] Although its original grandstand tragically succumbed to a fire, the racetrack continues to operate, retaining its status as one of America's oldest harness racetracks. Freehold also endured its own minor catastrophe: The Great Fire of Freehold, which erupted on October 30, 1873. The blaze reportedly started in a commercial establishment on Main Street, swiftly spreading to engulf a substantial portion of the village. Many wooden structures, including the venerable [Monmouth Courthouse](/Monmouth_County_Courthouse), were tragically consumed by the flames. [54]

Freehold also holds a somewhat overlooked, yet undeniably important, position in the annals of bicycle history. The celebrated cycling champion [Arthur Augustus Zimmerman](/Arthur_Augustus_Zimmerman) made the town his home during his illustrious racing career in the 1880s and 1890s. From 1896 to 1899, Zimmerman operated the Zimmerman Bicycle Co. within the town, producing bicycles affectionately known as the "Zimmy." Today, the [Metz Bicycle Museum](/Metz_Bicycle_Museum) in [Freehold Borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey) proudly houses the only known extant "Zimmy," a tangible link to this curious chapter of local history. [55]

#### 20th century

As the 20th century dawned, Freehold was a community increasingly fractured, particularly on the contentious issue of local tax dollars and their allocation for public works and vital [infrastructure](/Infrastructure) projects. [56] The Freeholders residing in the denser downtown area, clustered around the courthouse, harbored distinctly different visions for public spending compared to their counterparts living in the sprawling surrounding farmland. This inherent tension within the community reached a boiling point in 1916 when a severe [polio](/Polio) epidemic swept through Freehold, highlighting the urgent need for coordinated public health initiatives. [57] Following a period of intense and often acrimonious public debate, a referendum was finally held to determine the future of Freehold. Voters, with a decisive majority, opted to cleave the town into two separate municipalities, a rather drastic but ultimately necessary measure to resolve the enduring conflict of interests.

Thus, on April 15, 1919, [Freehold Borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey) formally extricated itself from [Freehold Township](/Freehold_Township,_New_Jersey). [28] Residents, with a pragmatic brevity, typically refer to the two distinct entities simply as the Borough and the Township. The Borough, encompassing the historical downtown area around the courthouse, naturally retained all existing government buildings along Court Street and Main Street, along with the prestigious designation as the county seat. [58] Freehold Township, comprising the agricultural communities that encircled the Borough, established its new administrative hub, a town hall complex, on Schanck Road. The geographic irony persists: the Township completely encircles the Borough, a perpetual embrace. On September 7, 1926, Freehold Borough further solidified its urban footprint by annexing additional territory from the surrounding Township. [58]

[[File:Freehold Township 911 Memorial.jpg|thumb|Freehold Township 911 Memorial located near Town Hall on Schanck Road]]

The early 20th century saw the farms within Freehold Township continue their trajectory of prosperity and success, contributing to a steady increase in population. However, the true demographic explosion occurred in the aftermath of [World War II](/World_War_II). By this time, advancements in transportation systems had reached a point where daily commutes to jobs in larger urban centers like [Newark](/Newark,_New_Jersey), [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), and [New York City](/New_York_City) became not just feasible, but commonplace. Major highways, notably [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) and [Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33), were instrumental in enabling this mass migration, allowing commuters to reside in Freehold and work in distant cities. The township, with a relentless efficiency, rapidly transformed, developing vast neighborhoods composed predominantly of suburban single-family homes. [18]

Soon enough, the township began to cultivate its own commercial and industrial enterprises, which swiftly grew to rival those of the more established Borough. [Brockway Glass Company](/Brockway_Glass_Company) erected its initial facility off Center Street in 1955, a site that saw significant expansion over subsequent decades before it finally ceased operations in 1991. [59][60] Today, the former Brockway Glass site is managed by [Iron Mountain](/Iron_Mountain_(company)), an enterprise information management services company, a modern testament to the ever-evolving landscape of commerce. [61] Not to be outdone, [3M](/3M) established a [magnetic tape](/Magnetic_tape) production facility in 1957. [62] The region's healthcare infrastructure also saw significant development with the opening of [CentraState Medical Center](/CentraState_Medical_Center) in 1971, then known as Freehold Area Hospital. This facility now serves as a crucial regional hospital for western [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey), southern [Middlesex County](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey), and portions of [Mercer](/Mercer_County,_New_Jersey) and [Ocean](/Ocean_County,_New_Jersey) counties. [63]

Not all industrial developments, however, were without their ecological consequences. In 1983, the [United States Environmental Protection Agency](/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency) regrettably designated the Lone Pine Chemical Site as a [superfund](/Superfund) site, a rather somber recognition of its environmental impact. [64] The site has been starkly characterized as "one of the worst environmental disasters in the country," a stark reminder of the costs of unchecked industrial ambition. [65] Fortunately, based on the EPA's latest five-year review in 2019, extensive remediation efforts have successfully contained the spill, a slow and painstaking process. [66] By 1990, with the grand opening of the [Freehold Raceway Mall](/Freehold_Raceway_Mall), a sprawling retail behemoth and the second-largest mall in the state, the township unequivocally cemented its status as a premier commercial center for [Central New Jersey](/Central_New_Jersey). [67]

As the township continued its relentless expansion, [Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33), which bisected the very heart of Freehold, became increasingly choked with traffic. This predictable congestion prompted studies suggesting the ambitious construction of a new freeway. The primary obstacle? The complete lack of space to widen the existing highway to four lanes between [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) and a crucial railroad bridge at its eastern end, which itself would have required extensive widening. After years of deliberation and bureaucratic inertia, the grand vision of a freeway was scaled back to a more modest, yet still vital, bypass of Freehold. Construction on the initial segment, stretching from near Sweetmans Lane ([County Route 527](/County_Route_527_(New_Jersey))) to [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey), concluded in 1972. Work then resumed, and the bypass was extended to Halls Mill Road in 1989. For decades, traffic was shunted through various detours, and congestion continued its inexorable worsening. The delay was further protracted when an endangered species was discovered squarely in the path of the proposed roadway, a testament to the unforeseen complexities that often plague human engineering. Finally, after a rather staggering 32 years of waiting, the bypass was fully completed in January 2003, providing some much-needed relief to the gridlock on [Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33) and [Route 33 Business](/New_Jersey_Route_33), though it never quite achieved a completely four-lane configuration between Halls Mills Road and the Howell Road intersection. [68][69]

#### 21st century

In the current century, Freehold Township continues its role as a significant employment hub, hosting thousands of jobs within its municipal borders, while simultaneously serving an ever-growing population of commuters who undertake the daily trek to neighboring metropolises such as [New York City](/New_York_City), [Newark](/Newark,_New_Jersey), [Trenton](/Trenton,_New_Jersey), and [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). The relentless rhythm of modern life, it seems, demands constant movement.

The township also carries the weight of national tragedy. Five of its residents tragically lost their lives in the [September 11, 2001, terrorist attack](/September_11_attacks) on the [World Trade Center](/World_Trade_Center_(1973%E2%80%932001)), their names now etched into the county's 9/11 memorial, a somber reminder of collective loss. [70][71]

The global [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic) predictably cast its long shadow over Freehold Township, much like it did over countless other communities worldwide. Early in the pandemic, the township (and [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey) at large) garnered media attention for the sheer volume of reported cases. A particularly poignant narrative emerged around the Fusco family of Freehold, who tragically lost five of their relatives during the initial months of the pandemic, with 19 other family members subsequently contracting the virus. [72][73] In a more pragmatic response to the changing times, the township adopted an ordinance in May 2020 designed to streamline the process for restaurant owners seeking permits for seasonal outdoor dining, a small but necessary adaptation to the new normal. [74] As of June 25, 2021, the township and county demonstrated a commendable efficiency, exceeding the [Biden Administration](/Biden_Administration)'s Coronavirus vaccine goal, with at least 73.5% of adults having received at least one dose, comfortably surpassing the national average of 65.6%. [75] A small victory in the face of an indifferent universe, perhaps.

### Geography

[[File:Manasquan River in Freehold Township.jpg|thumb|[Manasquan River](/Manasquan_River) flows through the township]]

According to the always precise, if somewhat dry, data from the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), Freehold Township encompasses a total area of 38.88 square miles (100.71 km2). Of this, a substantial 38.65 square miles (100.11 km2) is land, while a mere 0.23 square miles (0.59 km2), or 0.59%, consists of water. [1][2] One might consider it a rather land-locked existence for a place in New Jersey.

[[File:Apple picking in Freehold Township.jpg|thumb|During the autumn months, [hayrides](/Hayride) and [apple picking](/Apple_picking) (as pictured here) are among many popular recreational activities for township residents, along with nearby residents traveling from [North Jersey](/North_Jersey) and New York City]]

The township holds the rather unique distinction of completely encircling the borough of [Freehold](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey), an arrangement that makes it one of 21 pairs of "doughnut towns" found within the state of New Jersey. [76] This geographical embrace means it shares borders with several other municipalities: [Colts Neck](/Colts_Neck_Township,_New_Jersey), [Howell](/Howell_Township,_New_Jersey), [Manalapan](/Manalapan_Township,_New_Jersey), [Marlboro](/Marlboro_Township,_New_Jersey), and [Millstone Township](/Millstone_Township,_New_Jersey), all within [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey). Additionally, it touches [Jackson](/Jackson_Township,_New_Jersey) in neighboring [Ocean County](/Ocean_County,_New_Jersey). [77][78][79] It is important to clarify, for those easily confused, that the municipality of [Upper Freehold Township](/Upper_Freehold_Township,_New_Jersey) has no direct geographical or political connection to Freehold Township, despite the similar nomenclature.

Within the township's expansive borders lie two notable [unincorporated communities](/Local_government_in_New_Jersey) that also function as [census-designated places](/Census-designated_place): [East Freehold](/East_Freehold,_New_Jersey), with a 2020 Census population of 4,987, and [West Freehold](/West_Freehold,_New_Jersey), which tallied 13,596 residents as of 2020. [80][81]

Beyond these official designations, a scattering of other unincorporated communities, localities, and place names exist partially or entirely within the township. These include Blue Ball (which, for reasons lost to time, is now known as [Adelphia](/Adelphia,_New_Jersey)), [Burlington Heights](/Burlington_Heights,_New_Jersey), [82] [Georgia](/Georgia,_New_Jersey), Monmouth Heights (a name that suggests aspiration, if nothing else), Orchard Estates, Siloam, [Smithburg](/Smithburg,_New_Jersey), Southburg, and the rather descriptively named Stonehurst East and Stonehurst West. [83]

#### Ecology

According to the rather precise, if somewhat abstract, classifications of the [A. W. Kuchler](/A._W._Kuchler) U.S. [potential natural vegetation](/Potential_natural_vegetation) types, Freehold Township would theoretically host an Appalachian [oak](/Oak) (104) vegetation type, forming an Eastern [hardwood](/Hardwood) forest (25) vegetation form. [84] A testament to what nature *could* be, if left entirely to its own devices.

#### Major bodies of water

Given the township's particular geographic placement within [New Jersey](/New_Jersey), it serves as the crucial starting point, or [headwaters](/Headwaters), for numerous significant rivers, brooks, and streams that meander across the state. The township itself is situated on a [ridge](/Ridge) within the geographical [heartland of New Jersey](/Central_New_Jersey), [85][86][87][88][89] a distinction that often goes unnoticed by its inhabitants. Most sections of the township are characterized by the hillier terrain and fertile soil typical of the [Inner coastal plain](/Geography_of_New_Jersey), providing a rich foundation for agriculture. Conversely, the southeastern portions of the township transition into the flatter terrain and sandier soil more commonly associated with the [Outer coastal plain](/Geography_of_New_Jersey).

The majority of the township's hydrological network falls within the much larger [Raritan Valley Region](/Raritan_River), with many of its brooks and streams ultimately feeding into the aforementioned Raritan River. It also maintains a relatively close, if not immediate, proximity to the [Raritan Bay](/Raritan_Bay). Furthermore, Freehold Township is inextricably linked to the [Jersey Shore region](/Jersey_Shore), lying approximately 16 miles (26 km) west of the bustling shores of [Asbury Park](/Asbury_Park,_New_Jersey). [90] A small section of the township's southern portion even brushes against the northernmost reaches of the [Pine Barrens](/New_Jersey_Pine_Barrens), making it one of only two municipalities in [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey) that contribute to the [Toms River](/Toms_River) [watershed](/Drainage_basin), the bulk of which resides in [Ocean County](/Ocean_County,_New_Jersey) within the aforementioned Pine Barrens. [91]

