### Demographics

[[File:Freehold Jewish Center.jpg|thumb|The [Freehold Jewish Center](/Freehold_Jewish_Center) serves the rapidly growing [Jewish population](/Jews_in_New_Jersey) in the Freehold vicinity.]]
[[File:Co-Cathedral of St. Robert Bellarmine.jpg|thumb|[Co-Cathedral of St. Robert Bellarmine](/Co-Cathedral_of_St._Robert_Bellarmine)]]

The human element of Freehold Township, as meticulously cataloged by various censuses, reveals a constantly shifting, though perhaps not entirely surprising, demographic landscape.

#### 2010 census

The [2010 United States census](/2010_United_States_census) counted 36,184 individuals residing within Freehold Township, distributed among 12,577 households and 9,382 families. The resulting [population density](/Population_density) was a rather concentrated 939.8 per square mile (362.9/km2). The housing stock comprised 13,140 units, averaging a density of 341.3 per square mile (131.8/km2).

The racial composition of the population was recorded as follows: 84.32% (30,509 individuals) identified as [White](/White_(U.S._census)), 5.34% (1,931) as [Black or African American](/Black_(U.S._census)), a negligible 0.13% (47) as [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._census)), 7.03% (2,544) as [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._census)), and an even more minuscule 0.02% (7) as [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_(U.S._census)). Another 1.47% (531) were classified as being from [other races](/Race_and_ethnicity_in_the_United_States_census), with 1.70% (615) reporting two or more races. The [Hispanic or Latino](/Hispanic_(U.S._census)) demographic, encompassing any race, constituted 7.76% (2,808) of the total population. [23]

Of the 12,577 households, a significant 36.7% contained children under the age of 18, indicating a robust family presence. A comfortable majority, 61.4%, were married couples cohabiting, while 10.0% were female householders with no husband present. The remaining 25.4% were categorized as non-families, a rather clinical term for diverse living arrangements. Looking closer, 21.7% of all households were composed of individuals living alone, and 9.5% of these solitary residents were 65 years of age or older. The average household size was calculated at 2.75 persons, with the average family size slightly larger at 3.24. [23]

The age distribution of the population showed 24.3% under the age of 18, 7.5% between 18 and 24, 24.6% from 25 to 44, 30.7% from 45 to 64, and 13.0% who had reached the age of 65 or older. The median age across the township was 41.3 years, suggesting a fairly settled, mature population. Gender distribution revealed 97.9 males for every 100 females in the total population. For those aged 18 and older, the ratio was 96.9 males for every 100 females. [23]

The [American Community Survey](/American_Community_Survey) for 2006–2010, adjusted for inflation to 2010 dollars, indicated a [median household income](/Median_household_income) of $94,735, with a margin of error of +/- $5,749. The median family income stood higher at $112,094, with a margin of error of +/- $4,124. Males in the workforce commanded a median income of $85,099 (+/- $6,540), while females earned $48,926 (+/- $4,407). The per capita income for the township was $40,504 (+/- $2,006). A relatively small segment of the population, approximately 2.8% of families and 3.9% of the total population, found themselves below the poverty line. This included 4.6% of those under 18 and 4.0% of those aged 65 or over. [115]

