#### 2000 census

[[File:Lake Topanemus home.jpg|thumb|[Modern](/Modern_architecture) home located along [Lake Topanemus](/Lake_Topanemus)]]
[[File:West Freehold, New Jersey residential areas.jpg|thumb|The [West Freehold](/West_Freehold,_New_Jersey) neighborhood. The township's residential areas range from [suburban](/Suburb) to [exurban](/Exurb) in character and density.]]

As of the [2000 United States census](/2000_United_States_census) [15], the township was home to 31,537 people, residing in 10,814 households and forming 8,283 families. The population density at that time was 820.2 inhabitants per square mile (316.7/km2), a measure of how tightly packed human life had become. There were 11,032 housing units, distributed at an average density of 286.9 per square mile (110.8/km2). The racial composition of the township was predominantly [White](/White_(U.S._Census)) at 87.09%, followed by [African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)) at 5.12%, [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._Census)) at 5.15%, [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)) at a scant 0.14%, and [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_(U.S._Census)) at an even rarer 0.02%. Those identifying from [other races](/Race_(United_States_Census)) comprised 1.19%, while 1.30% reported two or more races. The collective [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) population, regardless of individual race, accounted for 5.19% of the total. [113][114]

Among the 10,814 households, a notable 37.8% included children under the age of 18, a testament to the ongoing cycle of human procreation. A solid 65.9% were married couples residing together, while 8.0% were female householders navigating life without a present husband. The remaining 23.4% were classified as non-families, a rather generic term for any arrangement that defies the traditional nuclear unit. Of all households, 20.0% consisted of individuals living alone, and 7.7% of these solitary residents were 65 years of age or older. The average household size was recorded as 2.76, with the average family size slightly larger at 3.21. [113][114]

The population's age distribution in the township was spread out: 25.3% were under the age of 18, 6.1% fell between 18 and 24, 31.2% were in the 25 to 44 age bracket, 25.5% were between 45 and 64, and 12.0% had reached 65 years of age or older. The median age was a rather precise 38 years. For every 100 females, there were 97.7 males, and for every 100 females aged 18 and over, the ratio adjusted slightly to 95.3 males. [113][114]

Financially, the median income for a household in the township was reported as $77,185, while the median income for a family was $89,845, figures that hint at a certain level of comfortable existence. Males, in a predictable pattern, commanded a median income of $62,545, significantly higher than the $36,668 earned by females. The per capita income for the township was $31,505. A small but persistent segment of the population existed below the poverty line: approximately 2.8% of families and 3.9% of the total population, including 4.8% of those under 18 and 5.1% of those aged 65 or over. [113][114]

### Economy

Given the township's relentless suburbanization over recent decades, its enviable proximity to the recreational allure of the [Jersey Shore](/Jersey_Shore), and its strategic location near major urban centers such as [New York](/New_York_City), [Newark](/Newark,_New_Jersey), [Trenton](/Trenton,_New_Jersey), and [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), Freehold Township has, with an almost inevitable trajectory, cemented its status as a longstanding economic engine within the [Central Jersey](/Central_Jersey) region. [67][116][117][118] It appears that convenience and consumerism are powerful economic drivers.

#### Agriculture

[[File:Farm in Freehold Township.jpg|thumb|One of many crop farms in the township]]
[[File:Wemrock Orchards.jpg|thumb|Wemrock Orchards on Route 33 Business]]
[[File:Battleview Orchards.jpg|thumb|Battleview Orchards on Wemrock Road]]
[[File:Orchard on Ely Harmony Road.jpg|thumb|Smaller orchard on Ely Harmony Road]]
[[File:Oakley Farmstead Community Garden.jpg|thumb|Community garden on the premises of the historic [Oakley Farmstead](/Walker-Combs-Hartshorne_Farmstead)]]

Despite the encroaching tide of suburban development in recent decades, the township's agricultural roots have, against all odds, managed to cling on. There remains a surprising number of working [crop farms](/Vegetable_farming), prestigious [thoroughbred farms](/Stud_farm), verdant [sod farms](/Sod), specialized [nurseries](/Plant_nursery), and flourishing [orchards](/Orchard) scattered throughout the township. This persistence of cultivation is a quiet rebellion against the concrete.

Among the notable agricultural enterprises that continue to operate are Brock Farms [119], the ever-popular Battleview Orchards [120], the Clayton Family Farm [121], Crawford Farms [122], the historically significant Oakley Farm [123], Reid Sod Farm [124], and the well-known Wemrock Orchards [125].

For those with a more refined palate, [Tomasello Winery](/Tomasello_Winery), originally established in [Hammonton](/Hammonton,_New_Jersey), maintains a satellite wine tasting room conveniently located within Wemrock Orchards. [126][127] One might say it’s an attempt to bring a touch of viticultural sophistication to the suburban landscape.

#### Commerce

[[File:Freehold Raceway Mall (2020).jpg|thumb|[Freehold Raceway Mall](/Freehold_Raceway_Mall)]]
[[File:Freehold Marketplace.jpg|thumb|Freehold Marketplace]]
[[File:Manalapan EpiCentre.jpg|thumb|[Manalapan EpiCentre](/Manalapan_EpiCentre) at night]]
[[File:Mount's Corner Shopping Plaza.jpg|thumb|[Mount's Corner Historic Shopping Plaza](/West_Freehold,_New_Jersey)]]
[[File:Jackson Premium Outlets.jpg|thumb|[Jackson Premium Outlets](/Jackson_Township,_New_Jersey) at daylight]]

Established way back in 1853, making it the nation's oldest half-mile harness racing track, [Freehold Raceway](/Freehold_Raceway) continues to offer discerning horse lovers and eager bettors the opportunity to witness the peculiar spectacle of [harness racing](/Harness_racing). [128] It's an enduring tradition, if nothing else.

A more contemporary monument to consumption, the [Freehold Raceway Mall](/Freehold_Raceway_Mall), was completed in August 1990 at a rather considerable cost of $125 million. It sprawls across a site covering more than 175 acres (71 ha) [118], conveniently located directly across from the Freehold Raceway, bisected by [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey). This "super-regional high-end shopping mall" boasts a [gross leasable area](/Gross_leasable_area) of a staggering 1,600,000 square feet (150,000 m2) [129], solidifying its position as the [third-largest mall in the state](/Shopping_malls_in_New_Jersey), trailing only [Westfield Garden State Plaza](/Westfield_Garden_State_Plaza) and the rather ambitious [American Dream Meadowlands](/American_Dream_(shopping_mall)). [130]

Beyond the behemoth that is the Freehold Raceway Mall, the township itself is dotted with a multitude of other shopping centers and plazas, catering to every conceivable retail whim. Diane & Co., a dress shop, even achieved a fleeting moment of fame by being featured on the [Oxygen Network's](/Oxygen_(TV_network)) reality show *[Jersey Couture](/Jersey_Couture)*. [131]

For those seeking a more... immersive form of distraction, iPlay America offers an indoor family entertainment and event center. Since its opening in November 2011, it has provided a predictable array of rides, arcade games, carnival games, and even a [Topgolf](/Topgolf) facility, alongside music venues, laser tag, shops, bars, and restaurants. [132][133] A veritable smorgasbord of manufactured fun.

**Main Street**

[Freehold Borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey), the very entity that the township so thoroughly surrounds, is home to Downtown Freehold, a quaint area situated along [East and West Main Street](/County_Route_537_(New_Jersey)). This historic downtown section offers a variety of eateries, bars, boutiques, and historical sites, along with other excursions that promise a taste of local charm. There have, of course, been ongoing plans to "revitalize" this downtown area, a common refrain in many an aging American town. [134]

Beyond the immediate Freeholds region, a plethora of other shopping destinations beckon, including the [Manalapan EpiCentre](/Manalapan_EpiCentre) (formerly known as the Manalapan Mall) in [Manalapan Township](/Manalapan_Township,_New_Jersey), the [Jackson Premium Outlets](/Jackson_Township,_New_Jersey) in [Jackson Township](/Jackson_Township,_New_Jersey), and The Shoppes in [Old Bridge Township](/Old_Bridge_Township,_New_Jersey). Truly, one is never far from an opportunity to spend.

#### Manufacturing

Freehold Township and its central Borough began their foray into commercial and industrial manufacturing during the latter part of the 19th and early 20th centuries, a predictable evolution for a growing region. Among the most prominent companies to establish operations in the township was the [Brockway Glass Company](/Brockway_Glass_Company), which erected a facility on Center Street in 1955. Brockway Glass, clearly finding the location agreeable, subsequently expanded its regional footprint with additional facilities in 1956, 1967, 1969, and 1976. However, even industrial giants are not immune to the relentless march of time and market forces; the company ultimately ceased its operations in the township in 1991. [59][60] Today, the sprawling former Brockway Glass site is now occupied by the Freehold campus of [Iron Mountain](/Iron_Mountain_(company)), a company specializing in [enterprise information management](/Enterprise_information_management) services, a rather stark transformation from glass bottles to digital data. [61]

In 1948, [Nestle](/Nestle) also established a production plant within the township, handling various logistics and engineering functions. This facility, after decades of operation, officially closed its doors in 2023, another quiet casualty of corporate restructuring. [135][136] Not to be forgotten, [3M](/3M) opened its magnetic tape production facility in 1957, contributing to the township's industrial diversity. [137]

#### Sports

In 2016, the Freehold Township Little League 12u baseball team achieved a moment of local glory, winning the New Jersey state championship and earning a berth in the [Mid-Atlantic Regional Tournament](/Little_League_World_Series). This marked the first time a team from the township had secured the state title since 2003, a testament to the cyclical nature of youth sports triumphs. [138] The following year, in 2017, the Freehold Township Little League 13U baseball intermediate division went a step further, claiming the United States Championship in the Little League Intermediate World Series tournament, defeating Wailuku, Hawaii, by a score of 6-4 in Livermore, California. [139]

The township's baseball achievements extend beyond the younger leagues. In 2004, the Freehold Township Senior League baseball team clinched the coveted [Senior League World Series](/Senior_League_World_Series) title. Under the leadership of manager Mike Brach of Freehold Township, this team made history, becoming the first from Freehold Township not only to reach the World Series but to emerge victorious. [140] One might say, they understand the subtle art of hitting a ball.

