### Education

[[File:Freehold Township High School.jpg|thumb|[Freehold Township High School](/Freehold_Township_High_School) located on [Elton-Adelphia Road](/County_Route_524_(New_Jersey))]]

The pursuit of knowledge, or at least the acquisition of credentials, is a structured affair in Freehold Township. Public school students from [pre-kindergarten](/Pre-kindergarten) through [eighth grade](/Eighth_grade) are educated under the auspices of the [Freehold Township Schools](/Freehold_Township_Schools). [194] As of the 2022–23 school year, this district, which comprises eight distinct schools, served an enrollment of 3,447 students. It employed 372.3 classroom teachers (on an [FTE](/Full-time_equivalent) basis), resulting in a [student–teacher ratio](/Student%E2%80%93teacher_ratio) of 9.3:1, a figure that suggests a reasonable level of individualized attention. [195]

The schools within the district, with their respective 2022–23 enrollment data provided by the ever-diligent [National Center for Education Statistics](/National_Center_for_Education_Statistics) [196], include:

*   The Early Childhood Learning Center [197], with 104 students in PreK.
*   C. Richard Applegate Elementary School [198], serving 377 students in grades K–5.
*   Joseph J. Catena Elementary School [199], with 426 students in grades K–5.
*   Laura Donovan Elementary School [200], educating 454 students in grades K–5.
*   Marshall W. Errickson Elementary School [201], with 453 students in grades K–5.
*   West Freehold Elementary School [202], serving 456 students in grades K–5.
*   Clifton T. Barkalow Middle School [203], accommodating 605 students in grades 6–8.
*   Dwight D. Eisenhower Middle School [204], with 578 students in grades 6–8. [205][206][207]

Students progressing to [ninth](/Ninth_grade) through [twelfth grades](/Twelfth_grade) attend either [Freehold Township High School](/Freehold_Township_High_School) or [Freehold High School](/Freehold_High_School), with their assignment determined by their specific home address as part of the [Freehold Regional High School District](/Freehold_Regional_High_School_District). [208] This district extends its educational reach to students from a broader geographical area, encompassing [Colts Neck Township](/Colts_Neck_Township,_New_Jersey), [Englishtown](/Englishtown,_New_Jersey), [Farmingdale](/Farmingdale,_New_Jersey), [Freehold Borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey), [Howell Township](/Howell_Township,_New_Jersey), [Manalapan Township](/Manalapan_Township,_New_Jersey), and [Marlboro Township](/Marlboro_Township,_New_Jersey). [209][210] Freehold Township High School distinguishes itself by hosting the Contemporary Global Studies Learning Center, while Freehold High School is home to the Medical Sciences Learning Center. Both of these specialized programs admit students on a selective basis, drawing from the entire Freehold Regional High School District, a testament to their focused academic offerings. [211] As of the 2022–23 school year, Freehold Township High School recorded an enrollment of 1,926 students and a teaching staff of 130.0 classroom teachers (FTE), yielding a [student–teacher ratio](/Student%E2%80%93teacher_ratio) of 14.8:1. [212] Concurrently, Freehold Borough High School had an enrollment of 1,409 students and 97.8 classroom teachers (FTE), resulting in a student–teacher ratio of 14.4:1. [213] The FRHSD board of education, a body composed of nine members, is elected to three-year terms from each of the constituent districts. [214] Each member's vote is weighted, totaling nine points, with Freehold Township allocated one member who possesses 1.4 votes. [215] A rather intricate system of representation.

For those students in Freehold Township with a more vocational bent, opportunities abound at specialized institutions such as [Biotechnology High School](/Biotechnology_High_School) (conveniently located within the township on [Kozloski Road](/County_Route_55_(Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey))), [High Technology High School](/High_Technology_High_School), the [Marine Academy of Science and Technology](/Marine_Academy_of_Science_and_Technology), [Communications High School](/Communications_High_School), and the [Academy of Allied Health & Science](/Academy_of_Allied_Health_%26_Science). These institutions are all part of the [Monmouth County Vocational School District](/Monmouth_County_Vocational_School_District) and are accessible to all qualified students in [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey) on a selective basis, offering specialized paths for focused learning. [216]

Higher education is also within reach, starting with [Brookdale Community College](/Brookdale_Community_College), a [public](/Public_university) [community college](/Community_college). Established in 1967, Brookdale serves as the community college for [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey), with its main headquarters situated in nearby [Lincroft](/Lincroft,_New_Jersey). To better serve its widespread student body, the college maintains regional satellite locations, including one conveniently located in Freehold Township on [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey), catering to the western Monmouth region. Furthermore, the college offers a valuable dual enrollment program, allowing qualified high school students to earn early collegiate credits, a pragmatic approach to academic acceleration. [217][218] [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University), in collaboration with Brookdale Community College, provides several bachelor's degree completion programs at Brookdale's Freehold Campus, demonstrating a commitment to accessible higher education. [219] In a more recent development, 2022 saw [Seton Hall University](/Seton_Hall_University) forge a partnership with Brookdale Community College to offer courses and resources for its College of Nursing program, also at Brookdale's Freehold campus. This collaboration includes dedicated laboratories, study areas, and additional cooperative arrangements with [CentraState Medical Center](/CentraState_Medical_Center), providing a comprehensive learning environment for aspiring nurses. [220]

### Historic district

*   Main article: [Monmouth Battlefield State Park](/Monmouth_Battlefield_State_Park)

The [Monmouth Battlefield Historic District](/Monmouth_Battlefield_State_Park), a substantial 1,819-acre (736 ha) [historic district](/Historic_district_(United_States)), is nestled within the larger expanse of [Monmouth Battlefield State Park](/Monmouth_Battlefield_State_Park). It straddles both sides of [Route 522](/County_Route_522_(New_Jersey)) and lies to the west of [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey), bordering Freehold Township and [Manalapan Township](/Manalapan_Township,_New_Jersey).

The site of the battlefield was once home to numerous colonial-era farmhouses, silent witnesses to the tumultuous events of the past. Regrettably, many of these structures did not survive the rapid and often unthinking development of the area in the 20th century. However, three of the original seven farmhouses that stood during the battle remain standing within the park today, offering a tangible link to history. These include the Sutfin Farmhouse (dating back to 1731), the Rhea-Applegate House (1745), and the [Craig House](/Craig_House_(New_Jersey)) (1746).

Further structures, though built after the pivotal battle, also contribute to the district's historical fabric. The Conover-Perrine House (1832) is located to the north of the park, erected on the very site of the original 18th-century Perrine House, and stands as an important example of late [Federal Architecture](/Federal_Architecture). The [Italianate](/Italianate) Cobb House, a later addition, was constructed in 1872 near the Conover-Perrine House. The Combs' Farmhouse (mid-18th Century), however, met a less fortunate fate, having been demolished sometime in the 1960s; its former location is now near the park's playground and [ice pond](/Ice_pond).

The district was officially recognized and added to the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on October 15, 1966. This designation was granted due to its profound significance in military history and for the enduring presence of colonial architecture and agricultural remnants that still evoke the fated events of the [Battle of Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth). [221] A quiet, persistent reminder of what once was.

