### Infrastructure

#### Public safety

Freehold Township, like any organized human settlement, maintains various departments dedicated to ensuring public safety. These emergency services are a testament to the collective, if sometimes begrudging, agreement to maintain order.

**Police**

The Freehold Township Police Department is structured into three primary divisions: patrol, investigation, and services. The current Chief of Police is George Baumann, who was appointed to the position in January 2020. His appointment followed the retirement of former chief Ernest Schriefer, who had served the department since 1980 and as chief since 2000. [222][223] The changing of the guard, it seems, is an inevitable part of every institution.

**Fire prevention**

The township, in its foresight, offers various fire prevention programs, presumably to mitigate the human tendency towards accidental combustion.

**Courses**

Freehold Township provides programs specifically designed to educate children on the critical importance of fire safety. These courses are, by all accounts, engaging for students and are offered conveniently at Township schools and other municipal buildings. [224] A pragmatic approach to a rather fiery problem.

**Squads**

Freehold Township relies on the dedication of two volunteer fire companies, a testament to community spirit, or perhaps a lack of sufficient tax revenue for professional services. [224]

**West Freehold**

*   Freehold Township Independent Fire Company #1 is situated on Stillwells Corner Road in [West Freehold](/West_Freehold,_New_Jersey). It was established in 1964 with the admirable goal of providing fire protection services across the entirety of Freehold Township. [225]
*   Freehold Township Fire Company No. 1 Station No. 2 is located in [Smithburg](/Smithburg,_New_Jersey).
*   Freehold Township Independent Fire Company No. 1 Station No. 3 serves the community of [Georgia](/Georgia,_New_Jersey).

**East Freehold**

*   East Freehold Fire Company, founded in 1972, can be found on Kozloski Road in [East Freehold](/East_Freehold,_New_Jersey). [226]

**First aid squads**

Freehold EMS, a vital service established in 1941, is based in [Freehold Borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey) but extends its pre-hospital care to residents of both the borough and the township. [227] Because emergencies, it seems, rarely respect municipal boundaries.

#### Transportation

##### Roads and highways

[[File:U.S. Route 9 in Freehold Township.jpg|thumb|[U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) northbound at the [Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33) interchange]]
[[File:New Jersey Route 33 in Freehold Township.jpg|thumb|[Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33) westbound at the [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) interchange]]

As of May 2010 [update], the township boasted a rather extensive network of 200.13 miles (322.08 km) of roadways. Of this total, 158.62 miles (255.27 km) were diligently maintained by the municipality itself, 26.49 miles (42.63 km) by [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey), and 15.02 miles (24.17 km) by the [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation). [228] A complex web, indeed.

Several major arteries slice through the township, facilitating the constant flow of traffic. Key state routes include [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey), [Route 18](/New_Jersey_Route_18), [Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33), and [Route 79](/New_Jersey_Route_79). Complementing these are the major county routes: [County Route 522](/County_Route_522_(New_Jersey)), [County Route 524](/County_Route_524_(New_Jersey)), [County Route 527](/County_Route_527_(New_Jersey)), and [County Route 537](/County_Route_537_(New_Jersey)).

For those seeking to escape the immediate confines of the township, access to [Interstate 195](/Interstate_195_(New_Jersey)) is readily available in neighboring [Howell Township](/Howell_Township,_New_Jersey), reachable via [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) or [Jackson Township](/Jackson_Township,_New_Jersey) via [County Route 537](/County_Route_537_(New_Jersey)). The [Garden State Parkway](/Garden_State_Parkway) entrance at Exit 100 is a mere ten miles east along [Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33) in [Tinton Falls](/Tinton_Falls,_New_Jersey). For those venturing further west, the [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike) entrance at exit 8 is approximately 10 miles (16 km) west on [Route 33](/New_Jersey_Route_33) in [East Windsor](/East_Windsor,_New_Jersey). The roads, it seems, are everywhere.

##### Public transportation

**Rail**

In the 19th and early 20th centuries, [Freehold Borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey) and Freehold Township were once served by two significant railway lines. One prominent railway in the area was the [Freehold and Jamesburg Agricultural Railroad](/Freehold_and_Jamesburg_Agricultural_Railroad), which was owned and operated by the venerable [Camden & Amboy Railroad Company](/United_New_Jersey_Railroad_and_Canal_Company). Surveying for this line commenced on September 8, 1851, grading began on October 19, 1852, and the first tracks were laid on April 4, 1853, a rather brisk pace for the era. [229] The initial section of the line officially opened for service on July 18, 1853. [230] The establishment of the Freehold & Jamesburg Agricultural Railroad played a crucial role in transforming the Freeholds into a regional [transportation hub](/Transportation_hub). [231] The other major railway serving the area was the [Central Railroad of New Jersey](/Central_Railroad_of_New_Jersey), which maintained a branch connecting the still-active former [Penn Central](/Penn_Central) line from [Jamesburg](/Jamesburg,_New_Jersey) to the CNJ's Seashore Branch and the New York and Long Branch line (now operated by NJ Transit) at [Matawan](/Matawan,_New_Jersey).

The Freehold and Jamesburg Railroad, however, was eventually abandoned by the early 1930s, a casualty of changing transportation landscapes. A 2.8-mile-long (4.5 km) segment of the former railroad's right-of-way was later approved for sale by the [New Jersey Board of Public Utility Commissioners](/New_Jersey_Board_of_Public_Utilities) to [Jersey Central Power & Light Company](/FirstEnergy) in 1966, though occasional freight service continued to utilize the [Freehold Industrial Track](/Freehold_Secondary). Meanwhile, the Central Railroad of New Jersey entered bankruptcy in the early 1970s and was ultimately absorbed into Conrail on April 1, 1976. Its freight service on the rails from Freehold to Matawan was terminated in 1979, with the rails themselves removed in 1980. Today, much of this former railway has been repurposed into a [rail-trail](/Rails-to-Trails_Conservancy), forming a section of the popular [Henry Hudson Trail](/Henry_Hudson_Trail).

A glimmer of hope for renewed passenger rail service exists in the form of the [Monmouth Ocean Middlesex Line](/Monmouth_Ocean_Middlesex_Line), a proposal by NJ Transit that envisions utilizing the same tracks as the Freehold Industrial Track. Both the township and its [neighboring borough](/Freehold_Borough,_New_Jersey) are identified as potential stops for this "MOM" Line. [232][233][234][235] A familiar story of ambition and bureaucratic deliberation.

As of now, the nearest operational train stations for residents of the township are located at [Aberdeen-Matawan](/Aberdeen-Matawan_station), [Asbury Park](/Asbury_Park_station), and [Long Branch](/Long_Branch_station_(NJ_Transit)) on the [North Jersey Coast Line](/North_Jersey_Coast_Line). For those needing to access the larger regional network, [Metropark](/Metropark_station) (in [Iselin](/Iselin,_New_Jersey)), [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick_station), and [Princeton Junction](/Princeton_Junction_station) on the [Northeast Corridor Line](/Northeast_Corridor_Line) are the closest options.

**Buses**

[NJ Transit](/NJ_Transit) provides extensive bus service, connecting communities along [U.S. Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) from [Lakewood Township](/Lakewood_Township,_New_Jersey) to [Old Bridge Township](/Old_Bridge_Township,_New_Jersey). For commuters heading to the urban sprawl, service to the [Port Authority Bus Terminal](/Port_Authority_Bus_Terminal) in [New York City](/New_York_City) is available via bus routes [131](/List_of_NJ_Transit_bus_routes_(100-199)), [135](/List_of_NJ_Transit_bus_routes_(100-199)), and [139](/List_of_NJ_Transit_bus_routes_(100-199)). For those venturing to the airport or other parts of [Newark](/Newark,_New_Jersey), the [67](/List_of_NJ_Transit_bus_routes_(1-99)) route provides access to [Newark Airport](/Newark_Liberty_International_Airport) and the city itself. Service to [Jersey City](/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey) is offered on the 64 and [67](/List_of_NJ_Transit_bus_routes_(1-99)) routes. Additionally, local service for shopping and other needs is provided by the [833](/List_of_NJ_Transit_bus_routes_(800-880)) and 836 routes. [236] For those with a more specific destination in mind, bus service from [Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) directly to [Wall Street](/Wall_Street) in New York's [Financial District](/Financial_District,_Manhattan) is available through the [Academy Bus Line](/Academy_Bus). [237]

Several designated bus stops for these routes are conveniently located along [Route 9](/U.S._Route_9_in_New_Jersey) within the township. Freehold Township, in its consideration for its commuting residents, offers two commuter parking lots, exclusively available to township residents, situated at the Freehold Mall Shopping Center and on Schibanoff Lane.

**Aviation**

Following the rather unceremonious closure of the [Marlboro Airport](/List_of_airports_in_New_Jersey), the closest options for short-distance flights to surrounding areas are now the [Old Bridge Airport](/Old_Bridge_Airport) in [Old Bridge Township](/Old_Bridge_Township,_New_Jersey) and [Monmouth Executive Airport](/Monmouth_Executive_Airport) in [Farmingdale](/Farmingdale,_New_Jersey). For major commercial air travel, residents must venture further. The nearest major commercial airport is [Trenton-Mercer Airport](/Trenton-Mercer_Airport), which offers domestic destinations primarily via [Frontier Airlines](/Frontier_Airlines). It is located approximately 24 miles (39 km) west, a journey of about 36 minutes by car. For a wider array of destinations, [Newark Airport](/Newark_Liberty_International_Airport), a significant hub for [United Airlines](/United_Airlines), is situated 35 miles (56 km) north of the center of Freehold Township, typically requiring about 50 minutes of travel time. [238][239]

**Ferry**

For those who prefer a more scenic, if less direct, route to [New York City](/New_York_City), ferry service is available through the [SeaStreak](/SeaStreak) company in [Highlands](/Highlands,_New_Jersey). This requires a drive of approximately 25–30 minutes from the [eastern section](/East_Freehold,_New_Jersey) of Freehold Township to reach the departing terminal. SeaStreak offers ferry trips to [Pier 11](/Pier_11/Wall_Street) (located on the East River at Wall Street) and [35th Street](/35th_Street_(Manhattan)) in [Manhattan](/Manhattan). [240] A rather pleasant way to avoid the predictable traffic, if time is not of the essence.

#### Healthcare

[[File:CentraState Medical Center.jpg|thumb|[CentraState Medical Center](/CentraState_Medical_Center)]]

[CentraState Medical Center](/CentraState_Medical_Center) stands as a prominent 287-bed regional hospital located directly within the township. It serves a significant swath of [Central New Jersey](/Central_Jersey), including parts of [Monmouth](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey), [Ocean](/Ocean_County,_New_Jersey), [Middlesex](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey), and [Mercer](/Mercer_County,_New_Jersey) counties. [241] The hospital operates as a partner of the [Atlantic Health System](/Atlantic_Health_System) and maintains an affiliation with [Rutgers Robert Wood Johnson Medical School](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_Medical_School), underscoring its commitment to medical education and advanced care. As part of the larger CentraState Healthcare System, it holds the distinction of being the county's fourth-largest employer, a significant economic contributor. [242]

Beyond CentraState, other regional hospitals serving the vicinity include the [Lakewood Township](/Lakewood_Township,_New_Jersey) division of [Monmouth Medical Center](/Monmouth_Medical_Center_Southern_Campus) and the [Old Bridge Township](/Old_Bridge_Township,_New_Jersey) division of [Raritan Bay Medical Center](/Raritan_Bay_Medical_Center).

For more specialized or complex medical needs, the closest major university hospitals are [Jersey Shore University Medical Center](/Jersey_Shore_University_Medical_Center) in [Neptune Township](/Neptune_Township,_New_Jersey), [Penn Medicine Princeton Medical Center